column1: I liked the question at the start of the survey that assessed if we read thoroughly. Most surveys I take use a nearly identical question to determine if we read directions, and after seeing it once it is no longer effective. Your question was unique and clever. Also, as someone interested in probability, I found the survey very intriguing.
Thanks for your time. I don't watch much sports.
Weird experiment.  There's virtually no way of knowing if the student's prediction was correct or not, nor how accurate the prediction was.
A prediction of 70% win isn't wrong... but 100% would have been. I think.

Your wording is confusing, though that may be on purpose. Declaring *probabilities* is very different from a *prediction* being correct or not -- something could have a 99% chance of being true, and still not occur -- the statistic may have been flawless, but that doesn't mean that the probable event is definitely going to happen.
Use different monikers other than A and B. It's harder to remain exactly. Especially when given so many \similar choices\"."
It's hard for me to say whether the prediction was *wrong,* given that the other student was speaking in terms of probability.

Interesting word choice, really had trouble deciding that even though the prediction gave the winning team a very low chance of victory, he technically did give them some chance which means his prediction is correct but extremely inaccurate in the given context because the team won 1/1 times(100%).  Made me think because no inflection was indicated in the way the information was given.
The first question about the banjo was smart to make sure the reader was paying attention
No, everything was clear and worked fine.

It's hard to gauge how accurate the prediction was based on a probability posed by the student. A question that comes to mind is: what is the student basing his calculation off of? Or is he just pulling numbers out of thin air?
